Before computing the Fractional Vegetation Cover (FVC), it is essential to first process satellite imagery data to obtain the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) dataset. To obtain the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI), an essential tool in remote sensing and ecology, the differential reflectivity between red and near-infrared wavelengths is analyzed14. This index is crucial for assessing the health and vitality of surface vegetation. Healthy vegetation generally absorbs more light in the red spectrum and reflects more in the near-infrared, while the reverse is true for unhealthy or sparse vegetation. NDVI values, which range from -1 to + 1, are calculated based on the reflectance values in these two spectrums, with higher values typically indicating denser vegetation15. The calculation of NDVI is expressed through Eq. (1) that evaluate these reflectance differences16:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
